&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/terms/derivation/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/terms/derivation/> ;
  schema:name "Derivation" ;
  schema:description "A Derivation is a pair (π, L) — a finite labeled tree π whose nodes carry formulas (or sequents) and a proof system L = (F, R) — such that every leaf carries an axiom or open hypothesis and every internal node carries the conclusion of some rule r ∈ R applied to its children. The defining structure: a derivation is a mechanically checkable certificate that a conclusion follows from hypotheses by a finite sequence of licensed rule applications. Its execution path is rule-governed, not guard-governed (unlike a procedure) and not state-transition-governed (unlike a process). The derivation emerges from proof search but is not the search itself — it is the finite witness the search produces." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/terms/derivation/> ;
  rdfs:seeAlso "Procedure, Process, Inquiry, ProofSystem, InferenceRule, NaturalDeduction, SequentCalculus, CurryHoward" ;
  schema:identifier &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/terms/derivation/> .

